      faq: {
        title: "FAQ",
        desc: "Frequently asked questions about HackIT installation, configuration, usage, and troubleshooting.",
        h_general: "General",
        h_troubleshooting: "Troubleshooting",
        h_advanced: "Advanced",
        items: [
          { q: "What is HackIT?", a: "A Python-based penetration testing CLI tool built with the Click library. It provides 23 tool modules for port scanning, web testing, vulnerability detection, reconnaissance, OSINT, SSL auditing, and more." },
          { q: "Is HackIT free?", a: "Yes, HackIT is open source. Free to use, modify, and distribute." },
          { q: "What platforms are supported?", a: "Linux, macOS, and Windows are all supported. Linux is recommended for wireless modules." },
          { q: "How do I run HackIT?", a: "Use python hackit/main.py [command] or python -m hackit.main [command] after cloning the repo and installing dependencies." },
          { q: "What are the CLI command groups?", a: "Commands are organized under: ports, web, vuln, recon, ssl, and util. Each group contains related tool modules." },
          { q: "What is the sozialengineer module?", a: "The sosialengineer module provides social engineering testing tools. It is one of 23 tool modules available under /hackit/." },
          { q: "Is there a web UI?", a: "Yes, HackIT includes a webUI module. Launch it with python hackit/main.py run." },
          { q: "How many themes are available?", a: "HackIT offers 15 CLI themes. Set your theme with python hackit/main.py config --theme <name>." },
          { q: "Wireless module shows no interfaces?", a: "Wireless modules require root/sudo access and a compatible wireless adapter. Run with python hackit/main.py wireless as root." },
          { q: "Error about missing pip dependencies?", a: "Ensure you have Python 3.10+ and run pip install -r requirements.txt from the project root." },
          { q: "AI agent not responding?", a: "Check your API key is set as the OPENAI_API_KEY environment variable or in ~/.hackit_config.json under ai_keys." },
          { q: "Permission denied for port scanning?", a: "Raw socket operations require elevated privileges. Run with Python under sudo or as administrator on Windows." },
          { q: "Module not found error?", a: "Make sure you are running from the project root directory where the hackit/ folder is located, or use python -m hackit.main from anywhere." },
          { q: "Can I create custom modules?", a: "The hackit agent is an interactive AI-powered assistant that can answer questions and help with penetration testing tasks. Run it with python hackit/main.py agent." },
          { q: "How do I configure the CLI appearance?", a: "Edit ~/.hackit_config.json and set the theme, accent, border, and prompt fields. Or use python hackit/main.py config --theme kali." },
          { q: "Is there a Docker image?", a: "No, HackIT does not have a Docker image. Simply clone the repo and install pip dependencies." },
          { q: "How are scan results stored?", a: "Each module outputs results to the console. There is no centralized result database \u2014 redirect output to a file with python hackit/main.py ports scan -p 80 --targets example.com > results.txt." },
          { q: "How do I update HackIT to the latest version?", a: "Run git pull origin main to pull the latest changes, then pip install -r requirements.txt --upgrade to update dependencies." },
          { q: "Can HackIT be used for bug bounty?", a: "Yes. Web modules like dir-finder, web-fuzzer, js-analysis, params, and 403-bypass are excellent for bug bounty reconnaissance and vulnerability discovery on authorized targets." },
          { q: "Does HackIT support custom wordlists?", a: "Yes. Most modules accept a --wordlist flag. Place custom wordlists anywhere and reference them by path. Default wordlists are under hackit/core/wordlists/." },
        ],
      },
